BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/MAC.00495.webp
CATEGORIES:Reading Circle,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260714T092446Z
DESCRIPTION:Join us for a reflective reading circle as part of our Disability Pride programming. Facilitated by Mira Brunner\, this session invites participants to gather around selected excerpts from books\, essays and memoirs by disabled writers and thinkers.\n\nTogether\, we will read aloud\, pause\, reflect\, and engage in conversation around the themes that emerge from the texts. Rather than analysing literature\, this session creates space for listening\, sharing lived experiences\, and exploring ideas of identity\, access\, care\, joy\, resistance\, and belonging through collective reading.\n\nNo prior reading or preparation is required. Whether you identify as a person with a disability\, are an ally\, or are simply curious to learn\, all are welcome to participate in this shared space of conversation and reflection.\n\nThis programme is presented as part of MAP's Disability Pride Month 2026 programming.\n\nReading lists were curated by Shrey Pathak and Mira Brunner.\n\n&nbsp\;\n\nSix Ways of Looking at Crip Time by Ellen Samuels\n\nAccess Intimacy\, Interdependence and Disability Justice by Mia Mingus\n\n10 Principles of Disability Justice\n\nBlast Radius of Disability from Johanna Hedva's - How to tell when we will Die\n\nRPD Bill: Diversity\, discourse and the disconnect by Shampa Sengupta\n\nHow to be a Person in the Age of Autoimmunity by Carolyn Lazard\n\nAIDS and Its Metaphors by Susan Sontag\n\nPreface to The Right to Maim by Jasbir Puar
DTEND:20260719T113000Z
DTSTART:20260719T083000Z
SUMMARY:Reading Together: A Disability Pride Reading Circle
UID:1336@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/reading-together-a-disability-pride-reading-circle/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Image-credit-_-Anjali-Pujari-scaled-e1784011452563.jpg
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260714T064437Z
DESCRIPTION:Image Credits: Anjali Pujari\nInspired by Beneath the Turning Sky\, Drawing the Unseen is a workshop led by Anjali Pujari for Deaf adults that invites participants to engage with the exhibition through slow looking\, reflection\, and creative exploration.\n\nMoving beyond the search for a single meaning\, the workshop encourages participants to observe details such as lines\, shapes\, textures\, patterns\, and empty spaces\, while reflecting on themes of memory\, ecology\, interconnectedness\, and imagination. Through guided prompts\, participants will consider what cannot always be seen but can be sensed\, remembered\, or imagined.\n\nResponding to the exhibition using a range of art materials\, each participant will create an individual artwork that reflects their own observations and experiences. The workshop celebrates multiple ways of seeing\, making\, and interpreting\, creating an inclusive space for creativity\, conversation\, and personal expression.\n\nDesigned specifically for Deaf adults\, Drawing the Unseen\,  offers an opportunity to connect with art at an unhurried pace and discover new ways of relating to the world through observation\, imagination\, and making.\n\nFor ISL translation\, please click here.
DTEND:20260718T073000Z
DTSTART:20260718T053000Z
SUMMARY:Drawing The Unseen
UID:1333@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/drawing-the-unseen/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Screenshot-2026-07-15-202955.png
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260715T150321Z
DESCRIPTION:Do you remember Shikari Shambu? What about Suppandi? We’ve all read stories of these beloved comic characters but do you wonder how they were created? Who drew them\; what stories that came before inspired their creators\; Did their designs change? Join us for a guided walk in Kannada to wonder about these and more questions. Get a sneak peek into the curatorial perspective and the history of Indian visual storytelling.\n\nThis programme is part of the celebration of the opening of A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling. \n\nThis exhibition is curated by the artist Amruta Patil\, in partnership with the Cité internationale de la bande dessinée et de l’image (CIBDI)\, Angoulême. It is supported by the Embassy of France in India and the French Institute in India within the larger framework of the Desibel project — an Indo-French initiative that brings together creators\, institutions and communities to shape the future of comics and visual storytelling within India’s animation\, visual effects\, gaming\, comics\, and extended reality (AVGC-XR) sector. A version of the exhibition will travel to Angoulême in January 2027 for the opening of the Angoulême International Comics Festival\, marking a milestone in the history of Indian comics in France.
DTEND:20260725T113000Z
DTSTART:20260725T103000Z
SUMMARY:Ink mattu kathe - A Kannada Guided Walk
UID:1345@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/ink-mattu-kathe-a-kannada-guided-walk/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/Website-cover-images-new-2026-01-27T094537.573.png
CATEGORIES:Reading Circle,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260714T115736Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credits: Aparna Nori \nFrom enchanted lands\, curses\, and boons to the realities of the modern climate crisis\, this reading circle invites participants to reflect on our evolving relationship with the natural worl. We invite you to explore stories and ideas that provoke\, challenge\, and inspire uncovering ways of understanding environmental change while drawing on collective wisdom\, resistance\, and imagination to learn how to listen to the planet again.\n\nDrawing from the themes explored in Beneath the Turning Sky the sessions engage with ecology and climate through a range of texts spanning folklore\, ecofeminism\, Indigenous knowledge systems\, environmental history\, and climate critique.\n\nUpon registration\, participants will be sent text extracts that will be discussed during the session. \n\nThis event is in conjunction with our ongoing permanent exhibition Beneath the Turning Sky. 
DTEND:20260718T110000Z
DTSTART:20260718T093000Z
SUMMARY:Beneath The Turning Sky: Reading Circle
UID:1330@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/reading-circle/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Screenshot-2026-07-13-184758.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260715T054234Z
DESCRIPTION:Facilitated by The Open Studio Project\, a collaborative practice by artists and art psychotherapists Devika Sundar and Roshni Bhatia\, this workshop invites participants into an exploration of memory\, myth\, and imagination through creative practice.\n\nBeginning with a shared exploration of the exhibition Beneath the Turning Sky\, participants will draw from their own lived experiences\, memories\, and imagination to create visual narratives that weave together inner and outer worlds and landscapes. Through image-making\, they are invited to explore the meeting points between memory\, myth\, place\, and the natural world\, considering how stories—both inherited and imagined—shape the ways we understand ourselves and the environments we inhabit. Rather than focusing on artistic skill or finished artworks\, the workshop emphasizes the creative process as a space for curiosity\, reflection\, dialogue and meaning-making.\n\nTaking place as part of Disability Pride Month\, the workshop is grounded in the values of accessibility\, inclusivity\, and care. Designed as a welcoming space for creativity and conversation\, it embraces diverse ways of learning\, making\, and participating\, inviting everyone to engage at their own pace and in ways that feel meaningful to them.\n\nNo prior artistic experience is required\, and all materials will be provided.
DTEND:20260719T073000Z
DTSTART:20260719T053000Z
SUMMARY:Memory\, Myth & Making
UID:1338@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/memory-myth-making/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/TC.2026.107-1.jpg
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260715T142643Z
DESCRIPTION:Image Credit: Panel from Vyasa: The Beginning by Sankha Banerjee\nJoin us for a guided walkthrough of the A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling as its curator Amruta Patil narrates the stories this country tells through lines. In this exhibition\, one can witness both the creation of new visual identities and the evolution of a nation through a vast body of works across time and space. Here\, kaavad and pattachitra scroll sitting alongside Amar Chitra Katha and Tinkle. Chacha Chaudhary next to the Phantom\, while contemporary graphic novels and web comics continue conversations that began centuries ago. \n\nThis programme is part of the celebration of the opening of A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling. \n\nThis exhibition is curated by the artist Amruta Patil\, in partnership with the Cité internationale de la bande dessinée et de l’image (CIBDI)\, Angoulême. It is supported by the Embassy of France in India and the French Institute in India within the larger framework of the Desibel project — an Indo-French initiative that brings together creators\, institutions and communities to shape the future of comics and visual storytelling within India’s animation\, visual effects\, gaming\, comics\, and extended reality (AVGC-XR) sector. A version of the exhibition will travel to Angoulême in January 2027 for the opening of the Angoulême International Comics Festival\, marking a milestone in the history of Indian comics in France.
DTEND:20260725T063000Z
DTSTART:20260725T053000Z
SUMMARY:Reading Between the Panels: A Curator’s Walkthrough
UID:1342@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/reading-between-the-panels-a-curators-walkthrough/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Untitled-design-10.jpg
CATEGORIES:Talks,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260714T095452Z
DESCRIPTION:What does it mean to belong? Who is responsible for creating the conditions in which every person can participate and feel valued?\n\nFor many autistic individuals and their families\, everyday life means navigating systems\, spaces and expectations that were not designed with them in mind\; leaving the work of adapting\, advocating and finding support to fall on families themselves.\n\nPresented as part of MAP’s Disability Pride Month 2026 programming\, this conversation brings together Bela Joshi and Sneha Joshi\, mother and daughter\, and mother and sister of an autistic family member\, in a dialogue shaped by lived experience and over a decade of work at Colours Centre for Learning. Across two generations\, they trace how the questions families ask\, and the support they seek change over time.\n\nAs a young mother raising an autistic son when awareness and services were scarce\, Bela found little institutional support\, and built her own community instead. Years later\, Sneha's questions as a sibling were different: about identity\, belonging and what it means to grow up alongside disability\, with even less language available for them. That process of finding\, and often having to build support shaped their understanding of interdependence: the idea that none of us moves through the world unsupported\, and that belonging is built by communities learning to rely on one another\, not by individuals becoming self-sufficient. It is also what grew into Colours Centre for Learning.\n\nTogether\, they bring a rare combination to this conversation: two generations\, two vantage points inside the same family\, and over a decade of shared commitment. Bela and Sneha ask what meaningful support can look like today for autistic individuals and for the families around them. Rather than framing inclusion as something families must continually strive for alone\, they invite us to imagine belonging as interdependence in practice: a responsibility shared across communities\, institutions and generations.\n\nThis programme is presented as part of MAP's Disability Pride Month 2026 programming.
DTEND:20260719T130000Z
DTSTART:20260719T120000Z
SUMMARY:Who Is Responsible for Belonging?
UID:1335@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/who-is-responsible-for-belonging/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/BTS-InstallViews-web-5.jpg
CATEGORIES:Drop-in Sessions,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260715T154220Z
DESCRIPTION:Ever wondered why most museums have Nataraja or Dancing Shiva in their collections? It is a result of multiple phenomena that happened during the 18th century. Art history\, modern dance\, physics\, West’s fascination for Eastern culture and more\, parallely played a part.\n\nThis month’s edition of Up\, Close and Centre will feature Abiraami from the MAP team. She looks at Nataraja from our second permanent exhibition Beneath the Turning Sky\, through the MAP Collection.\n\nUp\, Close &amp\; Centre is a series that allows audiences to engage with art in deeper and more meaningful ways by delving into the context\, narratives and makings of one artwork from our collection\, chosen by our team members.
DTEND:20260721T120000Z
DTSTART:20260721T113000Z
SUMMARY:Up\, Close and Centre: Nataraja
UID:1332@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/up-close-and-centre-nataraja/
END:VEVENT
